---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";

const ssrnUrl =
  "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=5984574";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy by Federico Rodrigo."
    />
  </head>

  <body>

    <header class="site-header">

      <a href="/" class="logo">
        Minimal Tolerance
      </a>

    <Header />

    <main>

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE BOOK
          </p>

          <h1>
            Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy
          </h1>

          <p class="lead">
            A book-length exploration of coercion,
            political authority, public goods,
            free riders and the limits of state power.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="book">

        <div class="container">

          <div class="book-grid">

            <div>

              <img
                src="/images/book-cover.jpg"
                alt="Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy"
              />

            </div>

            <div>

              <h2>
                About the Book
              </h2>

              <p>
                Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy develops the
                argument that the State is neither morally
                legitimate nor generally efficient, and that
                coercion therefore requires justification
                rather than presumption.
              </p>

              <p>
                The book culminates in the Theorem of
                Minimal Tolerance, a framework designed
                to identify the exceptionally narrow
                circumstances under which state coercion
                may be tolerated.
              </p>

            </div>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            STRUCTURE
          </p>

          <h2>
            Three Acts
          </h2>

          <p>
            The book is organized around three major themes:
            the problem of legitimacy, the problem of
            efficiency, and the institutional limits of
            political power.
          </p>

          <p>
            It progresses from the moral foundations of
            coercion, through the economic problems of
            centralized decision-making, and ultimately
            toward the formal statement of the theory.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The question is not whether power is legitimate.
          The question is how much power can be tolerated.
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <section class="ssrn">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            FOUNDATIONAL PAPER
          </p>

          <h2>
            Read the SSRN Paper
          </h2>

          <p>
            The original paper presents the formal theorem
            and serves as the theoretical foundation for
            the book.
          </p>

          <a
            href={ssrnUrl}
            class="primary"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Open on SSRN
          </a>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <footer>

      <p>
        © 2026 Minimal Tolerance · Federico Rodrigo
      </p>

    </footer>

  </body>

</html>
